ophers%20with%20social%20history%2C%20biography%2C%20accounts%20of%20the%20cultural%20and%20economic%20environment%2C%20and%20depictions%20of%20the%20quarrels%20and%20agreements%2C%20friendships%20and%20passions%20that%20characterised%20their%20communities.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EMeet%20the%20philosophers%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThe%20Visionaries%3C%2Fem%3E%20opens%20at%20the%20end%20of%201943.%20Each%20character%20is%20a%20very%20young%20woman%2C%20only%20in%20her%20thirties.%20But%20each%20is%20already%20possessed%20of%20a%20trained%20mind%2C%20formidable%20intelligence%20and%20a%20determination%20to%20make%20sense%20of%20life%2C%20the%20universe%2C%20and%20everything.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBeauvoir%20is%20writing%20her%20first%20philosophical%20essay%2C%20is%20about%20to%20publish%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.harpercollins.com.au%2F9780007204649%2Fshe-came-to-stay%2F%5C%22%3Eher%20first%20novel%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20has%20a%20play%20in%20the%20works.%20Weil%20has%20been%20asked%20by%20occupied%20France%E2%80%99s%20shadow%20government%20to%20draw%20up%20plans%20and%20scenarios%20for%20the%20political%20reconstruction%20of%20France%20(after%20her%20offer%20to%20go%20%E2%80%9Cto%20the%20front%20to%20die%20for%20her%20ideals%E2%80%9D%20was%20refused).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ERand%20is%20awaiting%20the%20publication%20of%20her%20debut%20book%2C%20%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.penguin.com.au%2Fbooks%2Fthe-fountainhead-9780141188621%5C%22%3EThe%20Fountainhead%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%E2%80%9Ca%20philosophical%20manifesto%20masquerading%20as%20a%20novel%E2%80%9D.%20And%20exactly%2010%20years%20after%20being%20driven%20out%20of%20Hitler%E2%80%99s%20Germany%2C%20Hannah%20Arendt%20is%20figuring%20out%20her%20next%20steps%2C%20reflecting%20that%20in%20%E2%80%9Cthese%20dark%20times%E2%80%9D%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20only%20had%20to%20find%20the%20courage%20in%20oneself%20to%20open%20one%E2%80%99s%20eyes%20%E2%80%93%20keep%20them%20open%20%E2%80%93%20to%20perceive%20the%20abysses%20of%20one%E2%80%99s%20own%20time%20with%20an%20alert%20mind.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAfter%20this%20opening%20chapter%2C%20the%20narrative%20jumps%20back%20a%20decade%20to%201933%2C%20and%20then%20progresses%20year%20by%20year%2C%20back%20to%20where%20it%20began.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFirst%2C%20we%20meet%20Simone%20de%20Beauvoir%2C%20who%20%E2%80%93%20with%20her%20life%20partner%20Jean-Paul%20Sartre%20%E2%80%93%20is%20associated%20with%20%E2%80%9C%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fwhat-makes-a-good-life-existentialists-believed-we-should-embrace-freedom-and-authenticity-204364%5C%22%3Eexistentialism%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%9D%20(though%20Eilenberger%20writes%20that%20she%20avoids%20the%20term).%20Existentialism%20argues%20each%20individual%20is%20a%20free%20agent%2C%20capable%20of%20crafting%20their%20own%20identity%20and%20existence%20through%20acts%20of%20the%20will.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBy%201943%2C%20Beauvoir%20was%20wrestling%20with%20one%20of%20existentialism%E2%80%99s%20core%20precepts%3A%20how%20individuals%20can%20achieve%20their%20best%20possible%20lives.%20She%20asked%2C%20why%20would%20someone%20even%20attempt%20this%3F%20After%20all%2C%20everything%20we%20do%20comes%20to%20nothing%20%E2%80%93%20because%20of%20time%E2%80%99s%20inexorable%20progress%20and%20our%20inevitable%20death%20%E2%80%93%20so%20why%20do%20anything%20at%20all%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAt%20that%20stage%2C%20her%20answer%20is%20that%20we%20should%20do%20something%20because%20we%20are%20in%20the%20world%20as%20acting%20creatures%2C%20and%20therefore%20should%20grasp%20our%20freedom%20to%20act%20while%20we%20are%20able.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3E%E2%80%98A%20heart%20that%20could%20beat%20right%20across%20the%20world%E2%80%99%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESimone%20Weil%2C%20whom%20we%20meet%20next%2C%20is%20pretty%20much%20the%20polar%20opposite%20of%20Beauvoir.%20Indeed%2C%20late%20in%20the%20volume%20Eilenberger%20notes%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20we%20compare%20Weil%E2%80%99s%20%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.goodreads.com%2Fen%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F322933%5C%22%3ENotebooks%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%20with%20Beauvoir%E2%80%99s%20diaries%20and%20writings%20from%20the%20same%20time%20%5B1941%E2%80%931942%5D%2C%20we%20have%20the%20extremely%20strange%20impression%20of%20a%20telepathic%20contact%20between%20two%20minds%20resonating%20tensely%20at%20either%20end%20of%20an%20infinite%20piece%20of%20string.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhere%20Beauvoir%20sees%20herself%20as%20comparatively%20separate%20from%20society%2C%20Weil%20had%2C%20as%20Beauvoir%20wrote%2C%20%E2%80%9Ca%20heart%20that%20could%20beat%20right%20across%20the%20world%E2%80%9D.%20Despite%20her%20physical%20fraility%20(and%20probable%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fdisease-evolution-the-origins-of-anorexia-and-how-its-shaped-by-culture-and-time-54571%5C%22%3Eanorexia%3C%2Fa%3E)%2C%20Weil%20was%20possessed%20by%20enormous%20passion%20and%20empathy.%20The%20wellbeing%20of%20everyone%20else%20in%20the%20world%20absorbed%20her%20thoughts%20and%20actions%20during%20her%20short%20life%20(she%20died%20in%201943).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFor%20years%2C%20Weil%20kept%20from%20her%20wages%20%E2%80%9Cprecisely%20the%20minimum%20sum%20assigned%20to%20unemployed%20factory%20workers%20on%20state%20support%2C%20while%20the%20rest%20she%20donate%5Bd%5D%20to%20needy%20or%20feeling%20comrades%E2%80%9D.%20And%20she%20directed%20her%20obedient%20parents%20to%20use%20their%20unoccupied%20apartment%20to%20house%20refugees%20%E2%80%93%20it%20once%20hosted%20a%20meeting%20between%20exiled%20communist%20leader%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Fbiography%2FLeon-Trotsky%5C%22%3ELeon%20Trotsky%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20new%20high%20command%20of%20the%20world%20revolution%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBorn%20into%20a%20Jewish%20family%2C%20Weil%20veered%20into%20a%20passionate%20and%20ascetic%20Christianity.%20For%20her%2C%20the%20point%20of%20being%20alive%20was%20to%20disappear%20into%20a%20future%20of%20nonbeing%2C%20confident%20that%20%E2%80%9CSupernatural%20love%20alone%20creates%20reality%E2%80%9D%20and%20that%20our%20meaning%2C%20if%20one%20can%20call%20it%20that%2C%20is%20to%20dissolve%20into%20a%20vessel%20for%20God%E2%80%99s%20will.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20is%20not%20a%20matter%20of%20%E2%80%9Cacting%E2%80%9D%2C%20in%20Beauvoir%E2%80%99s%20terms%2C%20but%20of%20leaving%20the%20world%20of%20authenticity%20and%20safety%20in%20favour%20of%20some%20notion%20of%20the%20divine.%20(Perhaps%20unsurprisingly%2C%20Weil%E2%80%99s%20often%20brilliant%20work%20has%20attracted%20less%20attention%20than%20that%20of%20her%20fellow%20characters%20in%20this%20book.)%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EAyn%20Rand%20and%20%E2%80%98no%20society%E2%80%99%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAyn%20Rand%20comes%20next%3A%20her%20family%E2%80%99s%20home%20and%20possessions%20were%20expropriated%20in%20the%201917%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fworld-politics-explainer-the-russian-revolution-100669%5C%22%3EOctober%20Revolution%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20on%20the%20grounds%20they%20were%20representatives%20of%20the%20Jewish%20%E2%80%9Cbourgeoisie%E2%80%9D.%20They%20fled%20to%20Crimea%2C%20then%20lived%20in%20poverty%20when%20they%20returned%20to%20St%20Petersburg%20(now%20named%20Petrograd)%20in%201921.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Russian%20jackboot%20she%20escaped%20was%20at%20least%20as%20violent%20as%20that%20of%20the%20Nazis%E2%80%99%20%E2%80%93%20as%20Simone%20Weil%20too%20argues%20in%20her%201933%20discussion%20about%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20structural%20similarity%20between%20newly%20fascist%20Germany%20and%20Stalin%E2%80%99s%20Soviet%20Union%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ERand%20made%20it%20to%20the%20United%20States%20in%201926%2C%20and%20began%20a%20career%20as%20a%20thinker%20and%20writer%20who%20named%20her%20philosophical%20position%20%E2%80%9C%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Ftopic%2Fobjectivism-philosophy%5C%22%3Eobjectivism%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%9D.%20Where%20Weil%20aimed%20to%20change%20the%20whole%20world%20through%20divine%20engagement%2C%20and%20Beauvoir%20perceived%20freedom%20as%20the%20freedom%20to%20act%20within%20a%20community%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fonlinelibrary.wiley.com%2Fdoi%2F10.1002%2F9781118324950.ch1%5C%22%3ERand%20insisted%20on%3C%2Fa%3E%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3Ethe%20concept%20of%20man%20as%20a%20heroic%20being%2C%20with%20his%20own%20happiness%20as%20the%20moral%20purpose%20of%20his%20life%2C%20with%20productive%20achievement%20as%20his%20noblest%20activity%2C%20and%20reason%20as%20his%20only%20absolute.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFor%20%E2%80%9Cman%E2%80%9D%2C%20read%20%E2%80%9CRand%E2%80%9D.%20Her%20most%20famous%20character%2C%20the%20architect%20Howard%20Roark%2C%20the%20protagonist%20of%20%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.penguin.com.au%2Fbooks%2Fthe-fountainhead-9780141188621%5C%22%3EThe%20Fountainhead%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%3C%2Fem%3E%20was%20after%20all%20based%20on%20herself.%20Roark%2C%20whose%20real-life%20admirers%20include%20Donald%20Trump%2C%20was%20a%20mouthpiece%20for%20objectivism%3A%20for%20reason%2C%20for%20facts%2C%20but%20never%20for%20compassion%20or%20empathy.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELike%20an%20early%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fthe-death-of-margaret-thatcher-and-the-legacy-of-thatcherism-13324%5C%22%3EMargaret%20Thatcher%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20Rand%20built%20an%20entire%20worldview%20based%20on%20there%20being%20no%20society%20%E2%80%93%20only%20self-focused%2C%20self-seeking%20individuals%2C%20capable%20of%20determining%20who%20and%20what%20they%20are%2C%20in%20perfect%20freedom.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHannah%20Arendt%2C%20with%20her%20mother%2C%20had%20fled%20Germany%20in%201933%20after%20they%20were%20arrested%20and%20interrogated%20by%20the%20Gestapo.%20For%20some%20years%2C%20she%20lived%20as%20an%20exile%20in%20France%2C%20later%20escaping%20to%20the%20United%20States.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHer%20initial%20writings%20explored%20the%20uncertainty%20of%20freedom%20in%20a%20world%20where%20events%20can%20strip%20the%20individual%20of%20identity%2C%20of%20nationality%2C%20of%20freedom%20%E2%80%93%20and%20even%20of%20life.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHer%20perspectives%20differ%20markedly%20from%20both%20existentialism%20and%20objectivism%3A%20Eilenberger%20observes%20that%2C%20for%20Arendt%2C%20%E2%80%9Cself-creation%20is%20always%20contingent%20on%20social%20and%20cultural%20conditions%2C%20from%20which%20no%20individual%20can%20fully%20escape%E2%80%9D.%20It%20is%2C%20she%20argued%20poignantly%2C%20political%20power%2C%20not%20self-determination%2C%20that%20sets%20the%20limits%20of%20our%20being.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20her%20case%2C%20this%20was%20the%20power%20of%20the%20Nazi%20machine%2C%20which%20destroyed%20so%20many%20members%20of%20her%20community%20%E2%80%93%20and%20which%20she%20had%20so%20narrowly%20escaped.%20Her%20philosophical%20concerns%20were%2C%20therefore%2C%20far%20from%20either%20individual%20self-realisation%20or%20self-abnegation.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ERather%2C%20she%20was%20concerned%20with%20what%20an%20individual%E2%80%99s%20responsibility%20might%20be%20in%20the%20face%20of%20overwhelming%20social%2C%20political%20and%20economic%20realities.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3E%E2%80%98The%20salvation%20of%20philosophy%E2%80%99%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThese%2C%20in%20brief%2C%20are%20the%20four%20philosophers%20who%20galvanised%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20salvation%20of%20philosophy%E2%80%9D.%20The%20lines%20and%20turns%20of%20their%20thinking%20were%20unpacked%20and%20reframed%20through%20much%20of%20what%20was%20going%20on%20in%20the%20salons%20of%20their%20twenties%2C%20or%20the%20writings%20of%20their%20thirties.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThey%20were%20deeply%20connected%2C%20through%20reading%2C%20through%20shared%20intellectual%20concerns%2C%20and%20in%20some%20cases%20through%20personal%20relationships%2C%20with%20the%20great%20philosophers%20who%20preceded%20them%20%E2%80%93%20all%20the%20way%20back%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fguide-to-the-classics-platos-republic-127724%5C%22%3EPlato%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20the%20fourth%20century%20BCE%20%E2%80%93%20and%20with%20their%20contemporaries.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESimone%20de%20Beauvoir%2C%20for%20example%2C%20was%20intimately%20connected%20to%20Jean-Paul%20Sartre%20in%20life%20and%20work.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fwittgenstein-tried-to-solve-all-the-problems-of-philosophy-in-his-tractatus-logico-philosophicus-but-he-didnt-quite-succeed-181719%5C%22%3ELudwig%20Wittgenstein%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%99s%20ethical%20and%20intellectual%20struggles%20with%20religion%20closely%20parallel%20Weil%E2%80%99s%20own%20(though%20there%20is%20little%20evidence%20they%20knew%20each%20other).%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fbooks%2F2014%2Faug%2F07%2Fwalter-benjamin-critical-life-howard-eiland-michael-w-jennings-review%5C%22%3EWalter%20Benjamin%3C%2Fa%3E%20was%20Arendt%E2%80%99s%20friend%20throughout%20their%20period%20of%20exile%20(and%20later%20was%20the%20subject%20of%20her%20writings).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fheideggers-notebooks-reveal-an-early-blindness-to-the-nazis-reality-24760%5C%22%3EMartin%20Heidegger%3C%2Fa%3E%20was%20the%20most%20intertwined%20with%20these%20philosophers.%20His%20writings%20influenced%20both%20Weil%E2%80%99s%20and%20Beauvoir%E2%80%99s%20work%2C%20particularly%20into%20the%20nature%20of%20being%2C%20and%20of%20human%20consciousness.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHe%20had%20also%20been%20Arendt%E2%80%99s%20teacher%20(and%20lover)%20at%20university%3B%20and%20though%20they%20were%20on%20opposite%20sides%20of%20the%20political%20divide%20%E2%80%93%20Heidegger%20became%20a%20Nazi%20in%201933%2C%20the%20same%20year%20Arendt%20was%20arrested%20by%20the%20Gestapo%20%E2%80%93%20Arendt%20reconnected%20with%20him%20in%201949%2C%20and%20remained%20his%20friend.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3E%E2%80%98Otherness%E2%80%99%3A%20danger%20or%20obligation%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20four%20women%20are%20complex%20characters%2C%20and%20not%20always%20likeable%2C%20being%20neither%20straightforward%2C%20nor%20straightforwardly%20admirable.%20Beauvoir%2C%20for%20example%2C%20declined%20to%20join%20a%201934%20general%20workers%E2%80%99%20strike%20on%20the%20grounds%20she%20was%20not%20part%20of%20society.%20She%20wrote%3A%20%E2%80%9CThe%20existence%20of%20Otherness%20remained%20a%20danger%20to%20me.%E2%80%9D%20In%20fact%2C%20%E2%80%9COtherness%E2%80%9D%20was%20such%20a%20danger%20that%20at%20this%20point%2C%20she%20claimed%20to%20identify%20with%20no%20one%20but%20Sartre.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EInterestingly%20though%2C%20she%20records%20a%20sharp%20criticism%20offered%20her%20by%20Simone%20Weil%20in%20a%20discussion%20they%20had%20about%20care%20of%20the%20Other%2C%20and%20what%20matters%20in%20the%20world.%20For%20Weil%2C%20the%20most%20important%20thing%20is%20to%20%E2%80%9Cfeed%20all%20the%20starving%20people%20of%20the%20earth%E2%80%9D.%20For%20Beauvoir%2C%20what%20matters%20is%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3Enot%20to%20make%20men%20happy%2C%20but%20to%20find%20the%20reason%20for%20their%20existence.%20%5BWeil%5D%20looked%20me%20up%20and%20down%3A%20%E2%80%9CIt%E2%80%99s%20easy%20to%20see%20you%E2%80%99ve%20never%20been%20hungry%E2%80%9D%2C%20she%20snapped.%20Our%20relations%20ended%20right%20there%20%5B%E2%80%A6%5D%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFair%20point.%20Or%20maybe%20not%20all%20that%20fair%2C%20since%20by%20the%20mid-1930s%2C%20Beauvoir%20was%20less%20inclined%20to%20consider%20the%20world%20a%20universe%20only%20of%20Beauvoir-plus-Sartre.%20Instead%2C%20she%20was%20beginning%20to%20take%20a%20more%20other-oriented%2C%20and%20more%20sensibly%20pragmatic%2C%20stance.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EPerhaps%20this%20was%20motivated%20by%20the%20fact%20the%20Beauvoir-plus-Sartre%20unit%20had%20become%20a%20polyamorous%20group%2C%20incorporating%20a%20worryingly%20young%20group%20of%20people%20who%20participated%20in%20their%20sexual%20and%20intellectual%20lives.%20The%20philosophers%E2%80%99%20ease%20with%20this%20complicated%20sexual%20engagement%2C%20which%20they%20characterised%20as%20%E2%80%9Cfamily%E2%80%9D%2C%20did%20not%20meet%20social%20norms.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBeauvoir%20was%20the%20subject%20of%20a%20year-long%20investigation%2C%20following%20complaints%20by%20the%20mother%20of%20one%20of%20the%20young%20people%20that%20she%20seduced%20her%20students%20and%20then%20passed%20them%20on%20to%20Sartre.%20This%20crime%20of%20%E2%80%9Cincitement%20to%20debauchery%E2%80%9D%20was%20not%20proven%2C%20for%20lack%20of%20evidence.%20At%20the%20same%20time%2C%20Sartre%20was%20sulking%20about%20his%20unsatisfying%20professional%20life%2C%20and%20insatiably%20sexually%20engaging%20with%20(it%20seems)%20pretty%20well%20anyone%20who%20entered%20his%20orbit.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3ESimone%20Weil%20and%20%E2%80%98the%20common%20people%E2%80%99%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20would%20imagine%20such%20experiences%20exposed%20Beauvoir%20to%20the%20limitations%20of%20both%20her%20philosophy%20and%20her%20capabilities.%20Certainly%2C%20such%20an%20awareness%20seems%20present%20in%20her%20explanation%20of%20why%20she%20and%20Sartre%20declined%20to%20join%20so%20many%20of%20their%20circle%20in%20travelling%20to%20Spain%20to%20serve%20in%20the%20war%20against%20Franco%3A%20that%20they%20were%20more%20likely%20to%20be%20%E2%80%9Ca%20nuisance%20rather%20than%20a%20help%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20evidence%20of%20this%2C%20she%20pointed%20out%20that%20Weil%20had%20gone%20to%20Spain%20to%20serve%20in%20the%20military%2C%20but%20when%20the%20infantry%20sensibly%20refused%20to%20arm%20her%2C%20Weil%20instead%20worked%20in%20the%20kitchens.%20(Her%20war%20ended%20when%20she%20stepped%20into%20a%20pot%20of%20boiling%20oil%20and%20was%20sent%20back%20to%20France%20to%20recover.)%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWeil%E2%80%99s%20passion%20for%20others%20often%20made%20her%20%E2%80%9Ca%20nuisance%20rather%20than%20a%20help%E2%80%9D.%20She%20identified%20strongly%20with%20the%20concept%2C%20at%20least%2C%20of%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20common%20people%E2%80%9D%2C%20but%20usually%20got%20things%20wrong.%20Despite%20her%20deeply%20fragile%20health%2C%20she%20took%20a%20sabbatical%20from%20her%20job%20as%20a%20philosophy%20teacher%20to%20work%20in%20a%20metals%20factory.%20This%2C%20she%20thought%2C%20would%20be%20%E2%80%9Creal%20life%E2%80%9D.%20Eilenberger%20gently%20teases%20this%20aspiration%2C%20but%20at%20the%20same%20time%20he%20notes%20her%20action%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3Estands%20in%20a%20respectable%20tradition%20of%20philosophical%20experiments%20whose%20declared%20objective%20was%20to%20turn%20one%E2%80%99s%20back%20on%20a%20presumably%20alienated%20world%20%5B%E2%80%A6%5D%20Like%20the%20Buddha%20fleeing%20the%20temple%2C%20or%20Diogenes%20in%20his%20barrel%2C%20or%20of%20course%20Thoreau%20building%20his%20hut%20on%20Walden%20Pond.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt%20was%20not%20an%20obviously%20useful%20experiment.%20Weil%20was%20a%20hopeless%20factory%20worker%2C%20causing%20herself%20injury%2C%20messing%20up%20the%20production%20line%2C%20and%20worsening%20her%20always-frail%20physical%20health.%20She%20was%20a%20hopeless%20social%20activist%20too.%20After%20her%20failure%20to%20solve%20the%20problems%20of%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Fevent%2FSpanish-Civil-War%5C%22%3ESpanish%20Civil%20War%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20and%20as%20France%20edged%20ever%20closer%20to%20war%20with%20Germany%2C%20she%20began%20developing%20suites%20of%20well-argued%20and%20utterly%20impractical%20solutions%2C%20all%20of%20which%20were%20rejected.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EArendt%20seems%20to%20have%20had%20a%20much%20stronger%20practical%20streak%20than%20did%20Weil%2C%20and%20a%20much%20clearer%20sense%20both%20of%20the%20complexities%20of%20being%20a%20human%20among%20other%20humans%2C%20and%20of%20the%20limitations%20on%20the%20fantasies%20of%20freedom%2C%20than%20either%20Beauvoir%20or%20Rand.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhile%20she%20was%20still%20living%20as%20a%20refugee%20in%20France%2C%20she%20was%20developing%20an%20understanding%20of%20what%20it%20is%20to%20be%20a%20pariah%3A%20considering%20how%20to%20preserve%20the%20only%20freedom%20pariahs%20have%20%E2%80%93%20the%20capacity%20to%20think%20for%20themselves.%20She%20was%20also%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fplato.stanford.edu%2Fentries%2Faugustine%2F%23Love%5C%22%3Ewondering%20about%20what%20love%20means%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EFoundations%20of%2020th-century%20thought%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EReading%20through%20this%20decade%2C%20and%20through%20the%20thinking%20that%20propelled%20the%20four%20women%20then%2C%20I%20had%20to%20keep%20reminding%20myself%20how%20dire%20their%20living%20conditions%20were.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFor%20the%20three%20Europeans%2C%20the%20looming%20dread%20of%20war%20and%20the%20nailing%20down%20of%20any%20freedom%20or%20opportunity%20framed%20their%20lives.%20Ayn%20Rand%20may%20have%20been%20far%20from%20Hitler%E2%80%99s%20reach%2C%20but%20she%20was%20unable%20to%20free%20her%20parents%20from%20the%20Great%20Terror%20of%20Stalinist%20Russia%2C%20she%20was%20having%20only%20uncertain%20success%20in%20her%20writing%2C%20and%20she%20lived%20with%20an%20unsatisfying%20husband.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThroughout%20all%20this%2C%20the%20Europeans%20at%20least%20sharpened%20and%20nuanced%20their%20understanding%20of%20what%20it%20is%20to%20be%20human%2C%20the%20point%20of%20being%20alive%2C%20what%20freedom%20means%2C%20and%20where%20our%20responsibilities%20lie.%20In%20doing%20so%2C%20they%20laid%20down%20some%20of%20the%20intellectual%20and%20ethical%20foundations%20that%20have%20inflected%20much%20of%20the%2020th%20century%2C%20and%20into%20our%20time.%20(Ayn%20Rand%E2%80%99s%20writings%2C%20on%20the%20other%20hand%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fwho-is-john-galt-ayn-rand-libertarians-and-the-gop-40033%5C%22%3Eprovided%20a%20textbook%20for%20the%20US%20Tea%20Party%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%93%20efficacious%20work%2C%20no%20doubt%2C%20but%20not%20work%20I%20can%20applaud.)%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBy%20the%20end%20of%20the%20book%2C%20I%20found%20I%20had%20changed%20my%20mind%20about%20the%20four%20women%20%E2%80%93%20primarily%20in%20the%20form%20of%20a%20significantly%20elevated%20appreciation%20for%20Simone%20de%20Beauvoir%20and%20an%20enhanced%20sympathy%20for%20Simone%20Weil.%20(I%20retained%20my%20confirmed%20enthusiasm%20for%20Arendt%2C%20and%20my%20equally%20confirmed%20disdain%20for%20Rand.)%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20also%20discovered%20a%20substantial%20admiration%20for%20the%20skill%20of%20the%20author%20and%20his%20translator.%20The%20clarity%20of%20voice%2C%20the%20respect%20paid%20to%20readers%20and%20to%20the%20four%20main%20subjects%2C%20and%20the%20little%20glimpses%20of%20humour%20(and%20larger%20glimpses%20of%20empathy)%20have%20left%20me%20a%20fan%20of%20this%20work.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EReaders%20who%20are%20not%20fans%20of%20philosophy%20shouldn%E2%80%99t%20fear%20the%20book%20will%20tangle%20them%20in%20the%20weeds%20of%20impenetrable%20lines%20of%20thought%3A%20its%20philosophy%20is%20made%20highly%20accessible.%20And%20the%20human%20stories%2C%20with%20all%20their%20tragedies%2C%20irritations%20and%20delights%2C%20are%20luminously%20and%20empathically%20crafted.%3Cimg%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20Conversation%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcounter.theconversation.com%2Fcontent%2F213895%2Fcount.gif%3Fdistributor%3Drepublish-lightbox-basic%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%